#compdef clarity-cli
# =============================================================================
# clarity-cli — Stacks Network's "Clarity smart contract
#               command-line interface" — the reference
#               compiler / type-checker / interpreter / REPL
#               for the Clarity smart-contract language that
#               powers the Stacks blockchain (BTC-secured L2).
#               Distinguishing from solc (Solidity), cairo-
#               compile (Cairo), move-cli (Move), and other
#               smart-contract language CLIs by:
#                 - 10 SUBCOMMANDS via clap v4 framework:
#                     * initialize       — initialize local VM
#                                          state database
#                     * generate-address — generate random
#                                          Stacks public address
#                     * check            — typecheck a contract
#                     * repl             — interactive REPL
#                     * eval-raw         — evaluate expression
#                                          without contract / DB
#                                          context
#                     * eval             — evaluate (read-only)
#                                          in contract context
#                     * eval-at-chaintip — evaluate at chain tip
#                     * eval-at-block    — evaluate at block hash
#                     * launch           — launch (deploy) a
#                                          contract
#                     * execute          — execute a transaction
#                                          (state-modifying call)
#                 - DECIDABILITY — Clarity is INTENTIONALLY non-
#                   Turing-complete; loops are bounded and the
#                   language is decidable, allowing programs to
#                   be statically analyzed for outcomes WITHOUT
#                   execution (contrast with Solidity which is
#                   Turing-complete and not decidable)
#                 - INTERPRETED ON-CHAIN — Clarity is NOT
#                   compiled to bytecode like EVM Solidity or
#                   Move; Stacks miners interpret Clarity source
#                   directly on-chain, giving exact semantics
#                   without bytecode translation risk
#                 - LISP-LIKE S-EXPRESSION SYNTAX — Clarity uses
#                   parenthesized prefix notation:
#                     (define-public (transfer (amount uint)
#                                              (recipient principal))
#                       (ok (stx-transfer? amount tx-sender recipient)))
#                 - STATIC TYPE SYSTEM with literal-only constant
#                   sizes — types like (buff 64), (string-ascii
#                   100), (response Ok Err), (optional T) — sizes
#                   must be compile-time constants
#                 - DEFINITE EXECUTION COSTS — every Clarity
#                   operation has a fixed cost; total contract
#                   gas can be UPPER-BOUNDED at compile time via
#                   `clarity-cli check --costs`
#                 - BTC-SECURED — Clarity contracts settle to
#                   Bitcoin via Stacks PoX (Proof-of-Transfer);
#                   no separate validator set
#                 - EPOCH-AWARE — Stacks blockchain progresses
#                   through "epochs" (2.0, 2.05, 2.1, 2.4, 3.0,
#                   etc.); clarity-cli accepts --epoch / --clarity-
#                   version flags for cross-epoch testing
#                 - TESTNET/MAINNET MODES — --testnet flag
#                   switches between testnet bootcode + block-
#                   limits and mainnet defaults
#                 - PRINCIPAL-BASED IDENTITY — contracts and
#                   accounts identified by Stacks address
#                   principals (e.g. SP3FBR2AGK5H9QBDH3EEN6DF8E
#                   K8JY7RX8QJ5SVTE.my-contract)
#                 - VM STATE DATABASE — persistent SQLite
#                   database via DB_PATH argument; supports
#                   block-replay-based eval-at-block
#               Used by: Stacks blockchain validators, Clarity
#               contract developers debugging contract logic
#               locally, security auditors statically analyzing
#               contracts pre-deployment, and as the reference
#               implementation of decidable smart-contract VMs.
#
# Author:  Stacks Network (formerly Blockstack PBC) — core
#          design by Aaron Blankstein + Jude Nelson + Diwaker
#          Gupta.  clarity-cli reference implementation in Rust.
#          Released ~2020 with Stacks 2.0 mainnet.  License: GPL-3.0.
# Source:  https://github.com/stacks-network/stacks-core
#          https://github.com/stacks-network/stacks-core/blob/master/contrib/clarity-cli/src/main.rs
#          https://github.com/stacks-network/stacks-core/blob/master/contrib/clarity-cli/Cargo.toml
# CLI:     main.rs — uses clap v4 (clap_derive Parser + Subcommand
#          attributes).  Headline focus: the LANGUAGE itself, not
#          the argparse framework (clap is already documented in
#          dozens of other Rust completions).
# Language: Clarity (https://github.com/stacks-network/stacks-core,
#           https://docs.stacks.co/write-smart-contracts/overview).
#           Smart-contract language for the Stacks blockchain.
#           Distinct from Solidity (Ethereum), Cairo (StarkNet),
#           Move (Aptos/Sui), Sway (Fuel), and other smart-
#           contract languages by being:
#              1. DECIDABLE — non-Turing-complete BY DESIGN;
#                 statically analyzable for outcomes without
#                 execution (no halting-problem barrier)
#              2. INTERPRETED ON-CHAIN — no bytecode compilation
#                 step; miners interpret Clarity source directly
#              3. LISP S-EXPRESSION SYNTAX — parenthesized prefix
#                 notation; familiar to Scheme/Racket users
#              4. UPPER-BOUNDED GAS — every operation's cost is
#                 statically known; total contract gas computable
#                 at compile time via `check --costs`
#              5. BITCOIN-SECURED — settles to Bitcoin via PoX
#                 (Proof-of-Transfer); no separate validator set
#              6. PRINCIPAL-BASED — addresses, contracts, and
#                 traits are all "principals" (sum type)
#              7. POST-CONDITIONS — transactions can attach
#                 post-conditions that ABORT the transaction if
#                 unexpected state changes occur (no
#                 "rugpull" guarantee)
#              8. RESPONSE TYPE — Clarity functions return
#                 (response Ok Err) — caller MUST handle
#                 success vs failure path (no implicit error
#                 propagation)
#              9. FIRST-CLASS TRAITS — interface-like trait
#                 definitions can be implemented + checked
#                 statically (similar to Rust traits)
#             10. NO REENTRANCY by construction — call patterns
#                 enforced by the language; reentrancy attacks
#                 (DAO-hack style) syntactically impossible
# License: GPL-3.0
# Status:  Stacks blockchain ~3,062+ stars on stacks-network/
#          stacks-core, ~$1B TVL, settles to Bitcoin since 2021.
#          Production language used in BNS (Bitcoin Name System),
#          ALEX DEX, Arkadiko stablecoin, CityCoins (now defunct),
#          and 400+ deployed contracts on Stacks mainnet.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — 94TH LANGUAGE: CLARITY
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy expands its
# **94TH PROGRAMMING LANGUAGE**: Clarity.  This expands the taxonomy
# from 93 to 94 documented programming languages.  Pattern: R645 Rust=69
# (chrono → Axis 15 OPENS) → R646 Go=69 (dateparse) → R647 TS-Node=69
# (date-fns → Axis 15 completes 1/1/1 three-language symmetry) → R648
# 94TH LANGUAGE (Clarity via clarity-cli THIS).  This completes the
# 3-leader-bump + 1-new-language micro-cycle.
#
# WHY CLARITY IS A DISTINCTIVE 94TH LANGUAGE:
#
#   1. DECIDABILITY BY DESIGN — Clarity is one of few production
#      programming languages that is INTENTIONALLY non-Turing-
#      complete.  Solidity, Move, Cairo, Vyper, Sway are all
#      Turing-complete (or close to it).  Clarity rejects
#      unbounded loops, recursion, and arbitrary callbacks
#      precisely so that contract behavior is statically
#      analyzable:
#         (define-private (factorial (n uint))
#           ;; FAILS — Clarity has no general recursion
#           ;; (n != 0) → recurse(n-1) is forbidden
#           ...)
#      Instead Clarity provides BOUNDED iteration via fold + map
#      with statically-known iteration counts on lists with
#      compile-time max-size.  This makes Clarity DECIDABLE in
#      the strict sense of decidability theory — programs are
#      guaranteed to halt and outcomes are computable.
#
#   2. INTERPRETED ON-CHAIN — Clarity contracts are stored as
#      SOURCE TEXT on the Stacks blockchain.  Miners interpret
#      the source directly.  Solidity → EVM bytecode (separate
#      compilation step; bytecode-level audits required).
#      Move → MVM bytecode + bytecode verifier.  Cairo → CAIRO
#      assembly + zk-proofs.  Clarity → SOURCE TEXT (no
#      compilation), giving exact 1:1 source-to-execution
#      semantics without an intermediate representation that
#      could introduce bugs.
#
#   3. UPPER-BOUNDED GAS — Because Clarity is decidable, the
#      MAXIMUM gas cost of any contract function is statically
#      computable.  `clarity-cli check --costs` reports the
#      worst-case gas for any path:
#         clarity-cli check --costs my-contract.clar
#         # Outputs: read-count: 5, read-length: 1024,
#         #         write-count: 3, write-length: 512,
#         #         runtime: 18200
#      Solidity / EVM can only estimate gas via profiling actual
#      executions — not statically bound.
#
#   4. LISP S-EXPRESSION SYNTAX — Clarity uses S-expressions
#      with prefix notation, distinct from C-family Solidity /
#      Move / Cairo / Sway:
#         (define-data-var counter uint u0)
#         (define-public (increment)
#           (begin
#             (var-set counter (+ (var-get counter) u1))
#             (ok (var-get counter))))
#      The LISP syntax has no operator precedence ambiguities;
#      every expression is parenthesized.
#
#   5. RESPONSE TYPE for explicit error handling — Clarity
#      public functions return `(response Ok Err)`:
#         (define-public (transfer (amount uint)
#                                   (recipient principal))
#           (if (>= (stx-get-balance tx-sender) amount)
#               (begin
#                 (try! (stx-transfer? amount tx-sender recipient))
#                 (ok true))
#               (err u100)))
#      Callers MUST handle the response — `(try!)` extracts Ok
#      or short-circuits with err; `(unwrap-panic!)` aborts on
#      err.  Solidity uses `require()` (revert-on-fail); Move
#      uses abort codes; Clarity makes error/success types
#      structural.
#
#   6. POST-CONDITIONS — Transactions can specify post-conditions
#      that ABORT the transaction if unexpected state changes
#      occur.  Example: "this transaction must NOT transfer more
#      than 100 STX from my account."  Post-conditions are
#      enforced at the protocol level, providing a "no
#      rugpull" guarantee.  Solidity has no equivalent built-in
#      mechanism.
#
#   7. PRINCIPAL-BASED IDENTITY — Addresses (standard or
#      contract) and traits are all "principals" with a unified
#      sum type:
#         (define-trait sip-010-trait
#           ((transfer (uint principal principal (optional (buff 34)))
#                      (response bool uint))))
#         (define-public (call-sip010 (token <sip-010-trait>)
#                                      (amount uint))
#           (contract-call? token transfer amount tx-sender ...))
#      Traits provide interface-like polymorphism with static
#      checking.
#
#   8. NO REENTRANCY BY CONSTRUCTION — Clarity contracts cannot
#      receive callbacks in the middle of execution because the
#      call pattern is structured: a contract calls another
#      contract via `contract-call?`, and the called contract
#      cannot call back into the caller before the current
#      execution completes.  This MAKES THE DAO-HACK REENTRANCY
#      ATTACK SYNTACTICALLY IMPOSSIBLE.  Solidity / EVM allow
#      reentrancy and require manual mutex patterns or
#      checks-effects-interactions discipline.
#
#   9. BITCOIN-SECURED via PROOF-OF-TRANSFER (PoX) — Stacks
#      blockchain achieves consensus by transferring BTC to
#      Stacks miners.  No separate validator set, no separate
#      PoS slashing.  Stacks blocks settle to Bitcoin blocks,
#      inheriting Bitcoin's security.  Clarity contracts thus
#      have Bitcoin-grade settlement guarantees, distinct from
#      Ethereum (PoS) or Solana (PoH).
#
#  10. STACKS EPOCHS — Stacks blockchain progresses through
#      epochs (2.0, 2.05, 2.1, 2.4, 3.0, Nakamoto) each
#      potentially adding new Clarity language features.
#      clarity-cli's --epoch + --clarity-version flags allow
#      testing contracts against specific epoch semantics.
#
# Cross-language CLI library taxonomy after R648:
#   * 94 languages documented (Clarity is the 94th)
#   * 386 total CLI library variants
#   * Rust=69 / Go=69 / TS-Node=69 (three-way tie at leaderboard top)
#   * Axis 9 / Logging: 6/6/6 three-language symmetric
#   * Axes 10 + 13 + 14: 2/2/2 three-language symmetric
#   * Axes 7 + 11 + 12 + 15: 1/1/1 three-language symmetric
#
# Languages documented prior to R648 (selected new languages):
#   * R605 ATS2 (patsopt) — 84th
#   * R612 Logtalk (logtalk_backend_select) — 85th
#   * R616 M/MUMPS (ydbinstall.sh) — 86th
#   * R620 REXX (regina) — 87th
#   * R624 Austral (austral) — 88th
#   * R628 Onyx (onyx) — 89th
#   * R632 TXR (txr) — 90th
#   * R636 Ioke (ioke) — 91st
#   * R640 Falcon (falcon) — 92nd
#   * R644 Slang (slangc) — 93rd
#   * R648 Clarity (clarity-cli THIS) — 94th
#
# Note on choice of clarity-cli vs alternatives:
#   * clarity-cli is the OFFICIAL REFERENCE Clarity CLI from the
#     stacks-network/stacks-core repository (the canonical
#     Stacks node implementation).  Alternative Clarity tooling
#     (clarinet by Hiro Systems) exists but is a separate
#     developer-focused framework with its own taxonomy slot
#     (clarinet is in our blacklist at line 4037).  clarity-cli
#     is the BARE-METAL Clarity execution + checking CLI,
#     analogous to solc for Solidity.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE clarity-cli CLI — clap v4 derive + 10 subcommands
#
# clarity-cli's CLI is in contrib/clarity-cli/src/main.rs.  Uses
# clap v4 derive macros for Parser + Subcommand:
#
#     use clap::{Parser, Subcommand};
#
#     #[derive(Parser)]
#     #[command(name = "clarity-cli")]
#     #[command(about = "Clarity smart contract command-line interface")]
#     struct Cli {
#         #[command(subcommand)]
#         command: Commands,
#     }
#
#     #[derive(Subcommand, Debug)]
#     enum Commands {
#         #[command(name = "initialize")] Initialize { ... },
#         #[command(name = "generate-address")] GenerateAddress,
#         #[command(name = "check")] Check { ... },
#         #[command(name = "repl")] Repl { ... },
#         #[command(name = "eval-raw")] EvalRaw { ... },
#         #[command(name = "eval")] Eval { ... },
#         #[command(name = "eval-at-chaintip")] EvalAtChaintip { ... },
#         #[command(name = "eval-at-block")] EvalAtBlock { ... },
#         #[command(name = "launch")] Launch { ... },
#         #[command(name = "execute")] Execute { ... },
#     }
#
# Common flags across subcommands:
#   --testnet                Use testnet configuration
#   --epoch EPOCH            Stacks epoch (2.0, 2.05, 2.1, 2.4, 3.0)
#   --clarity-version V      Clarity language version
#   --costs                  Output cost information
#   --output-analysis        Output contract analysis
#   --contract-id ID         Contract identifier
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/stacks-network/stacks-core/blob/master/contrib/clarity-cli/src/main.rs
# clap v4 #[derive(Parser)] + #[derive(Subcommand)] definitions.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

local -a _clarity_cmds _clarity_epochs _clarity_versions
_clarity_cmds=(
    'initialize:Initialize a local VM state database'
    'generate-address:Generate a random Stacks public address'
    'check:Typecheck a potential contract definition'
    'repl:Typecheck and evaluate expressions in a stdin/stdout loop'
    'eval-raw:Typecheck and evaluate an expression without contract or database context'
    'eval:Evaluate (in read-only mode) a program in a given contract context'
    'eval-at-chaintip:Evaluate a program in a given contract context at the chain tip'
    'eval-at-block:Evaluate a program in a given contract context at a specific block'
    'launch:Launch (deploy) a contract'
    'execute:Execute a transaction (state-modifying call) on a contract'
    'help:Show help for a subcommand'
)
_clarity_epochs=(
    '1.0:epoch 1.0'
    '2.0:epoch 2.0'
    '2.05:epoch 2.05'
    '2.1:epoch 2.1'
    '2.2:epoch 2.2'
    '2.3:epoch 2.3'
    '2.4:epoch 2.4'
    '2.5:epoch 2.5'
    '3.0:epoch 3.0 (Nakamoto)'
    '3.1:epoch 3.1'
)
_clarity_versions=(
    'Clarity1:Clarity v1'
    'Clarity2:Clarity v2'
    'Clarity3:Clarity v3'
)

_arguments -C \
    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
    '(- *)'{-V,--version}'[show version]' \
    '1: :->cmd' \
    '*::arg:->args' \
    && ret=0

case $state in
    cmd)
        _describe -t commands 'clarity-cli subcommand' _clarity_cmds && ret=0
        ;;
    args)
        case $words[1] in
            initialize)
                _arguments \
                    '--testnet[use testnet bootcode and block-limits instead of mainnet]' \
                    '--epoch=[Stacks epoch to use]:epoch:->epoch' \
                    '1:db path:_files -/' \
                    '2:allocations file:_files' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            check)
                _arguments \
                    '--contract-id=[contract identifier]:contract_id:_default' \
                    '--output-analysis[output contract analysis]' \
                    '--costs[output cost information]' \
                    '--testnet[use testnet configuration]' \
                    '--clarity-version=[Clarity version]:version:->version' \
                    '--epoch=[Stacks epoch]:epoch:->epoch' \
                    '1:contract file:_files' \
                    '2:db path:_files -/' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            repl)
                _arguments \
                    '--testnet[use testnet configuration]' \
                    '--epoch=[Stacks epoch]:epoch:->epoch' \
                    '--clarity-version=[Clarity version]:version:->version' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            eval-raw)
                _arguments \
                    '--testnet[use testnet configuration]' \
                    '--epoch=[Stacks epoch]:epoch:->epoch' \
                    '--clarity-version=[Clarity version]:version:->version' \
                    '1:program file:_files' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            eval)
                _arguments \
                    '--costs[output cost information]' \
                    '--epoch=[Stacks epoch]:epoch:->epoch' \
                    '--clarity-version=[Clarity version]:version:->version' \
                    '1:contract id:_default' \
                    '2:db path:_files -/' \
                    '3:program file:_files' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            eval-at-chaintip)
                _arguments \
                    '--costs[output cost information]' \
                    '--epoch=[Stacks epoch]:epoch:->epoch' \
                    '--clarity-version=[Clarity version]:version:->version' \
                    '1:contract id:_default' \
                    '2:db path:_files -/' \
                    '3:program file:_files' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            eval-at-block)
                _arguments \
                    '--epoch=[Stacks epoch]:epoch:->epoch' \
                    '--clarity-version=[Clarity version]:version:->version' \
                    '1:block hash:_default' \
                    '2:contract id:_default' \
                    '3:db path:_files -/' \
                    '4:program file:_files' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            launch)
                _arguments \
                    '--costs[output cost information]' \
                    '--output-analysis[output contract analysis]' \
                    '--testnet[use testnet configuration]' \
                    '--epoch=[Stacks epoch]:epoch:->epoch' \
                    '--clarity-version=[Clarity version]:version:->version' \
                    '1:contract id:_default' \
                    '2:contract file:_files' \
                    '3:db path:_files -/' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            execute)
                _arguments \
                    '--costs[output cost information]' \
                    '--epoch=[Stacks epoch]:epoch:->epoch' \
                    '--clarity-version=[Clarity version]:version:->version' \
                    '1:db path:_files -/' \
                    '2:contract id:_default' \
                    '3:function name:_default' \
                    '4:sender address:_default' \
                    '*:argument:_default' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            help)
                _describe -t commands 'subcommand' _clarity_cmds && ret=0
                ;;
        esac
        case $state in
            epoch)
                _describe -t epochs 'Stacks epoch' _clarity_epochs && ret=0
                ;;
            version)
                _describe -t versions 'Clarity version' _clarity_versions && ret=0
                ;;
        esac
        ;;
esac

return ret
